Now let me analyze the code more carefully. Looking at the `ImportOrderingRule.kt` file, specifically lines 76-93, I can see the issue:

```kotlin
val sortedImportsWithSpaces = mutableListOf<ASTNode>()
sortedImports.fold(null as ASTNode?) { prev, current ->
    val index1 = if (prev == null) -1 else importSorter.findImportIndex((prev.psi as KtImportDirective).importPath!!)
    val index2 = importSorter.findImportIndex((current.psi as KtImportDirective).importPath!!)

    var hasBlankLines = false
    for (i in (index1 + 1) until index2) {
        if (importSorter.patterns[i] == PatternEntry.BLANK_LINE_ENTRY) {
            hasBlankLines = true
            break
        }
    }
    if (hasBlankLines) {
        sortedImportsWithSpaces += PsiWhiteSpaceImpl("\n\n")
    }
    sortedImportsWithSpaces += current

    return@fold current
}
```

The problem is that when `prev` is `null` (first import), `index1` is set to `-1`. Then the loop checks from `(index1 + 1)` which is `0` until `index2`. If there are blank line entries at the beginning of the patterns (before the first import's index), they will be detected and blank lines will be inserted.

For the config `*, |, javax.**, java.**, |, kotlinx.**, kotlin.**`, when there are no imports matching `*`, the first import (e.g., `java.nio.file.Files`) will have an index that comes after the first `|`. The loop from `0` to that index will find the `|` and insert a blank line.

Let me trace through the logic more carefully by looking at what happens with the test case:

